result.text:
A normal company wants its shareholders to hold their stock for a long time. They aim to grow together on a stable foundation, reward shareholders who believed in them, and build a relationship of mutual trust.

But what about GameStop? The current state of GameStop feels like a company where you’re an idiot if you’re not making money through options or swing trading. At times, it even seems like the CEO himself is encouraging this behavior. Just look at how Ryan Cohen retweeted HAN and JACKIE at such critical moments.

It’s a stark contrast to two or three years ago. Back then, they subtly created an atmosphere where if you didn’t DRS or HODL, it felt like the world was going to end. Now, they make it seem like you’re a fool if you’re not selling or not buying.

I would like to ask Mr. Cohen politely—are you a thug? Is this the kind of teaching your father passed down to you? Is this the kind of advice you’re getting from Larry Cheng, now playing professor at Harvard?

It’s funny. Throughout my life, I’ve seen many criminals. But perhaps they were the more innocent ones. The real people who rob others of their lives do so under a mask of goodwill, armed with every legal loophole, descending upon us like saints.      #gme #ryancohen
